  <h1>How Class Action Settlements Work</h1>
  <p><em>Reviewed by Aspen Lockwood (AL), Editor-in-Chief. Updated May 2026.</em></p>
  <h2>Preliminary approval</h2>
  <p>After parties agree to a settlement, plaintiff&rsquo;s counsel moves for preliminary approval. The court reviews the proposed settlement for facial fairness and approves the notice plan. Class members then receive notice by mail, email, or publication explaining their rights: participate, opt out, or object.</p>
  <h2>Claims filing period</h2>
  <p>Class members typically have 60&ndash;180 days to submit claim forms. The form may require proof of purchase, account numbers, or attestation of harm. Claims rates vary enormously &mdash; from under 1% in small-claims consumer cases to 50%+ in securities cases where institutional investors file systematically.</p>
  <h2>Final approval hearing</h2>
  <p>The court holds a fairness hearing under Fed. R. Civ. P. 23(e). Class members may object or appear. The court evaluates the settlement&rsquo;s fairness using the factors from <em>Grinnell</em> or the local circuit&rsquo;s equivalent. Final approval orders the settlement and approves attorney fees.</p>
  <h2>Appeals period</h2>
  <p>Objectors have 30 days to appeal the final approval order. Professional objectors (who file boilerplate objections to extract side payments) can delay distributions by 12&ndash;18 months. After appeals are exhausted or the deadline passes, the fund is distributed.</p>
  <h2>Distribution</h2>
  <p>Valid claims are processed, invalid claims are rejected, and checks or ACH payments go out. Uncashed checks and residual funds may go to cy pres recipients or supplement individual payments in a second distribution.</p>
  <h2>Where to go from here</h2>
  <p>See <a href="/guides/types-of-class-action-cases">types of class action cases</a> and <a href="/guides/filing-a-class-action-claim">how to file a claim</a>.</p>
